Bio: Born into slavery in Ulster county, New York, but escaped with her daughter to freedom in 1826. Her best-known extemporaneous speech on gender inequalities, "Ain't I a Woman?", was delivered in 1851 at the Ohio Women's Rights Convention in Akron, Ohio.
On December 1, 1955, Rosa Parks sparked a pivoting point in US History when she refused to obey bus a driver's order that she give up her seat in the colored section to a white passenger.
Elizabeth II has quietly become one of the longest-reigning monarchs in English history. In addition, Elizabeth II has started new trends toward modernization and openness in the royal family.

Bio: Betty Ford was known both as a former First Lady and as the founder of the Betty Ford Clinic for substance abuse recovery.

Marie Curie became the first woman to win a Nobel Prize and the only woman to win the award in two different fields (physics and chemistry). Curie's efforts led to the discovery of polonium and radium and, the development of X-ray.

Biologist Rachel Carson alerted the world to the environmental impact of fertilizers and pesticides. Her best-known book, Silent Spring, led to a presidential commission that largely endorsed her findings and helped to shape a growing environmental consciousness.

Graham is called the Mother of Modern Dance. She was a dancer, choreographer, and teacher for more than 70 years, and during that time she changed the landscape of dance forever. An unlikely candidate for a dance diva, she was shorter and more muscular than the principal ballet dancers of her time.
